llectual property, or internal system information.\\n\\n**Threat Actor:** Cybercriminal\\n\\n**Attack Vector:** The attack begins by scanning for publicly accessible S3 buckets.\\n\\n**Detection and Response:** Regularly audit S3 bucket permissions and monitor API calls to your S3 buckets using AWS CloudTrail. Respond to unauthorized access attempts by adjusting permissions or adding additional security measures like encryption.\\n\\n**Likelihood:** High\\n\\n**Dependencies:** The S3 bucket needs to be publicly accessible for this threat to be possible.\\n\\n**Mitigation(s):**\\n- Ensure all S3 buckets are not publicly accessible unless necessary.\\n- Regular audits of S3 bucket permissions.\\n- Enable bucket versioning to restore data in case of accidental deletion or manipulation.\\n\\n**Log & Monitor:**\\n- Monitor AWS CloudTrail logs for unauthorized API calls.\\n- Use AWS Config to monitor and record bucket configuration changes.\\n- Set up S3 bucket event notifications for object level operations.\\n\\n#\\n## Threat: Application-level DoS Attacks ##\\n\\n**Description:** Application-level DoS attacks target a specific feature or function of a network, application, or service with the intent to overwhelm it with traffic and render it unusable.\\n\\n**Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs):**\\n- **Tactic(s):** Impact\\n- **Technique(s):** T1499 - Endpoint Denial of Service\\n- **Procedure(s):** Attackers exploit a vulnerability in the application or saturate its resources, rendering it unavailable to legitimate users.\\n\\n**Risk:**\\n- **Attack Vector:** Network\\n- **Attack Complexity:** Medium\\n- **Privileges Required:** None\\n- **User Interaction:** None\\n- **Social trends:** Trending\\n- **Ease of exploitation:** Medium (real-world)\\n\\n**Real-World Example:** In 2013, a DoS attack on the BBC took its website and iPlayer service offline for several hours.\\n\\n**Impact if Exploited:** Could lead to extensive downtime or reduced functionality of the