ces.\n\n**Mitigation(s):**\n- Ensure comprehensive logging is enabled across all AWS services, including CloudFront and S3.\n- Regularly audit and optimize logging configurations to capture all critical events.\n- Implement centralized logging solutions for real-time monitoring and analysis.\n- Use AWS CloudWatch and AWS GuardDuty to detect and alert on suspicious activities.\n\n**Log & Monitor:**\n- Monitor AWS CloudTrail for changes to logging configurations or suspicious activities.\n- Use AWS CloudWatch to set up alerts for critical events and anomalies in log data.\n- Implement automated log analysis tools to detect patterns indicative of malicious behavior.\n\n---\n\n## Threat: Exploitation of Insufficient Rate Limiting on APIs ##\n\n**Description:** An attacker could exploit the lack of rate limiting on APIs exposed via CloudFront to perform brute force attacks or overwhelm the service, causing denial of service or unauthorized access through credential stuffing attacks. \n\n**Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs):**\n- **Tactic(s):** Initial Access, Denial of Service\n- **Technique(s):** Brute Force (T1110), Network Denial of Service (T1498)\n- **Procedure(s):** An attacker continuously sends requests to API endpoints without rate limiting, attempting to guess credentials or exhaust resources.\n\n**Risk:**\n- **Attack Vector:** Network\n- **Attack Complexity:** Low\n- **Privileges Required:** None\n- **User Interaction:** None\n- **Social trends:** Common\n- **Ease of exploitation:** High\n\n**Real-World Example:** An attacker targets an API exposed via CloudFront without rate limiting, using automated scripts to perform credential stuffing attacks.\n\n**Impact if Exploited:** Unauthorized access, service disruption, and potential data breaches due to credential compromise.\n\n**Threat Actor:** Cybercriminal\n\n**Attack Vector:** The attack exploits insufficient rate limiting on APIs exposed via CloudFront.\n\n**Detection and Response:** Implement rate limiting, monitor API usage patterns, and establish alert mechanisms for unusual access attempts.\n\n**Likelihood:** Medium\n\n**Dependencies:** Lack of rate limiting on publicly exposed APIs.\n\n**Mitigation(s):**\n- Implement rate limiting and throttling on all API endpoints to prevent abuse.\n- Use AWS API Gateway to enforce quotas and rate limits for API access.\n- Monitor API usage patterns and set up alerts for unusual access attempts.\n- Implement AWS WAF to filter and block malicious requests targeting APIs.\n\n**Log & Monitor:**\n- Monitor AWS CloudTrail for excessive API access attempts.\n- Use AWS CloudWatch to alert on anomalies in API traffic patterns.\n- Implement logging and monitoring to detect and respond to credential stuffing attacks.\n\n---\n\n## Threat: Social Engineering Attack Leading to Unauthorized CloudFront Access ##\n\n**Description:** An attacker could use social engineering tactics to gain access to CloudFront management interfaces, leading to unauthorized changes or data access. This could involve phishing or pretexting to trick employees into revealing credentials or sensitive information.\n\n**Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs):**\n- **Tactic(s):** Initial Access, Credential Access\n- **Technique(s):** Phishing (T1566), Valid Accounts (T1078)\n- **Procedure(s):** An attacker sends phishing emails or uses other social engineering methods to obtain credentials from employees with access to CloudFront management.\n\n**Risk:**\n- **Attack Vector:** Human\n- **Attack Complexity:** Medium\n- **Privileges Required:** None\n- **User Interaction:** Required\n- **Social trends:** Increasing\n- **Ease of exploitation:** High\n\n**Real-World Example:** An attacker uses a phishing campaign to obtain login credentials from an employee, gaining access to the organization's CloudFront configuration.\n\n**Impact if Exploited:** Unauthorized access to AWS resources, potential data breaches, and configuration changes leading to service disruption.\n\n**Threat Actor:** Cybercriminal\n\n**Attack Vector:** The attack exploits human vulnerabilities through social engineering tactics.\n\n**Detection and Response:** Implement strong security awareness training, use multi-factor authentication, and monitor for account anomalies.\n\n**Likelihood:** Medium\n\n**Dependencies:** Human susceptibility to social engineering tactics.\n\n**Mitigation(s):**\n- Conduct regular security awareness training to educate employees on recognizing	string	\N	2025-05-07 22:31:14.072906-05	2025-05-08 15:48:28.363624-05
